docs.abstract: Upscale developments downtown have drawn a demographic that is largely wealthy and white, making some others feel unwelcome.
docs.snippet: Upscale developments downtown have drawn a demographic that is largely wealthy and white, making some others feel unwelcome.
docs.lead_paragraph: DURHAM, N.C. — “Downtown just ain’t black enough for me,” Paul Scott wrote in The Durham Herald-Sun a couple of months ago. A minister and local newspaper columnist, Mr. Scott was echoing a sentiment voiced by many of the city’s longtime African-American residents: The city center does not feel welcoming to them anymore.

headline.main: In a Revived Durham, Black Residents Ask: Is There Still Room for Us?
headline.print_headline: When Home No Longer Looks the Same

docs.abstract: Intel and its chief executive, Brian Krzanich, are in the hot seat over Meltdown and Spectre, two chip security issues that were disclosed last week.
docs.snippet: Intel and its chief executive, Brian Krzanich, are in the hot seat over Meltdown and Spectre, two chip security issues that were disclosed last week.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — In 1994, Intel faced a public relations crisis over an elusive mathematics glitch that affected the accuracy of calculations made by its popular Pentium computer chips. After insisting that the problem would not affect many people, the company succumbed to public pressure and recalled the chips, costing it $475 million.

headline.main: Intel Faces Scrutiny as Questions Swirl Over Chip Security
headline.print_headline: Intel Chip Security Is Scrutinized After Disclosure of Hacking Openings

docs.abstract: Mark Zuckerberg’s return to focusing more on the welfare of users may limit short-run profits but should improve sustainability.
docs.snippet: Mark Zuckerberg’s return to focusing more on the welfare of users may limit short-run profits but should improve sustainability.
docs.lead_paragraph: Mark Zuckerberg is discovering the cost of factory-farming Facebook’s users. The $550 billion social network’s success in harvesting advertising dollars through mass-appeal content has made it very profitable. The snag is that users are increasingly unhappy. The founder and chief executive’s return to focusing more on their welfare may limit short-run earnings but should improve sustainability.

headline.main: The New Facebook’s Long-Term Benefit to the Bottom Line

docs.abstract: The Abraaj Group, a private equity investor in emerging markets, said it is removing its founder, Arif Naqvi, after clients questioned the firm’s governance.
docs.snippet: The Abraaj Group, a private equity investor in emerging markets, said it is removing its founder, Arif Naqvi, after clients questioned the firm’s governance.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Abraaj Group, one of the largest private equity firms specializing in emerging markets, said on Friday that its founder, Arif Naqvi, would no longer oversee the firm’s asset management business.

headline.main: Chief of Leading Investment Firm Steps Aside After Client Complaints
headline.print_headline: Complaints Spur Abraaj To Remove Its Founder

docs.abstract: A three-judge panel upheld the finding that the Robin Thicke song infringed on the copyright of Marvin Gaye’s “Got to Give It Up.”

headline.main: ‘Blurred Lines’ Verdict Upheld by Appeals Court
